Analyse_Student_Population_Impact_On_Local_Business_and_Employment

Authored by: Shivani Satav

Duration: 100 mins

Level: Intermediate

Pre-requisite Skills: Python, Pandas, Matplotlib, Seaborn

Scenario

Local councils, educational institutions, and business chambers often need to understand how the presence of studentsespecially international studentsaffects the local economy. In many urban areas, student populations contribute significantly to demand for housing, retail, hospitality, and part-time jobs. This analysis scenario investigates whether there is a correlation between the number of students in different suburbs and local business performance (in terms of business count and employment opportunities).

By merging and analysing the datasets, decision-makers can identify patterns, trends, and correlations to guide economic and urban planning strategies.

User Story

As a city economic development planner, I want to analyse how student populations influence the number of businesses and jobs in local suburbs, So that I can make informed policy decisions, plan infrastructure, and create initiatives to support both student communities and local businesses.

Introduction

The document aims to explore the relationship between student population size and local business economic indicators across different suburbs and years.

This analysis follows these main stages:

Data Collection Importing datasets on student populations, residents' education attendance, and local business establishment details.

Data Cleaning & Preprocessing Renaming columns, filtering relevant records, and aligning suburb names for consistency.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) Summarising and visualising student and business trends over time, identifying top student-concentrated suburbs.

Correlation Analysis Merging datasets to calculate statistical relationships between student counts, business counts, and job counts.

Visual Analysis Using line plots, bar charts, and scatter plots to present patterns and relationships in an easily interpretable way.

The outcome of this work can assist local governments, universities, and business networks in making data-driven decisions that maximise economic and social benefits from student populations

Data Collection

This section retrieves the datasets required to analyse the relationship between student populations and local business activity using the City of Melbourne Open Data API.

We define a reusable helper function collect_data(dataset_id) that:

  1. Constructs the dataset export URL dynamically using the provided dataset ID.
  2. Sends an HTTP GET request to the API with parameters to:
    • Select all available fields (select: '*')
    • Retrieve all available records (limit: -1)
    • Standardise language (lang: 'en') and timezone (timezone: 'UTC')
  3. If the request is successful:
    • Decodes the response from CSV format.
    • Loads the data into a Pandas DataFrame for further cleaning and analysis.
  4. If the request fails:
    • Raises an exception with the returned HTTP status code.

Datasets Fetched:

  • Residents Profiles Education Attendance(residents-profiles-by-clue-small-area)
    Contains information about residents attending educational institutions, broken down by suburb and year.
  • Business Establishments & Jobs (business-establishments-and-jobs-data-by-business-size-and-industry)
    Contains annual counts of businesses and jobs by suburb and industry classification.

These datasets form the foundation for correlating student counts with local business metrics.

In[2]:
def collect_data(datasetid):
    base_url = 'https://data.melbourne.vic.gov.au/api/explore/v2.1/catalog/datasets/'
    format = 'csv'
    url = f'{base_url}{datasetid}/exports/{format}'

    params = {
        'select': '*',
        'limit': -1,
        'lang': 'en',
        'timezone': 'UTC'
    }

    response = requests.get(url, params=params)
    if response.status_code == 200:
        csv_content = response.content.decode('utf-8')
        dataset = pd.read_csv(StringIO(csv_content), delimiter=';')
        return dataset
    else:
        raise Exception(f"Failed request {response.status_code} for {datasetid}")

Data Cleaning & Preprocessing

This section prepares the raw student and business datasets for analysis by standardising column names, filtering relevant records, handling missing values, and aggregating data where necessary.

  1. Students Dataset (students_df)

  • Rename Columns for clarity

  • Filter Education-Related Attendance: Only rows where category equals "Education Institution Attendance" and sub_category equals "Attending" are retained.

  • Standardise Suburb Names: Whitespace is removed and names are title-cased to ensure consistency.

  • Convert Numeric Fields and Handle Nulls:

  • Year and Student Count are converted to numeric types.

  • Rows missing critical values (Year, Suburb, or Student Count) are dropped.

  • Remaining missing Student Count values are filled with 0.

  1. Business Dataset (business_df)

  • Rename Columns to standard names

  • Aggregate by Year and Suburb: Sum the number of businesses (Business Count) and total jobs (Jobs) for each suburb and year.

  • Standardise Suburb Names: Remove extra whitespace and parentheses, and title-case names for consistency.

  • Convert Numeric Fields and Handle Nulls:

  • Convert Year, Business Count, and Jobs to numeric types.

  • Drop rows missing critical values (Year, Suburb, or Business Count).

  • Fill missing Jobs values with 0.

The cleaned datasets are now consistent, numeric fields are properly formatted, and missing or inconsistent data is handled, making them ready for merging and analysis

In[3]:
# =============================
# 1. Clean and Prepare Students Data
# =============================
# Rename columns
students_df.rename(columns={
    'geography': 'Suburb',
    'year': 'Year',
    'value': 'Student Count'
}, inplace=True)

# Filter only education-related attendance data
edu_students = students_df[
    (students_df['category'].str.lower() == 'education institution attendance') &
    (students_df['sub_category'].str.lower() == 'attending')
].copy()

# Standardise suburb names
edu_students['Suburb'] = edu_students['Suburb'].str.title().str.strip()

# Convert numeric fields and handle nulls
edu_students['Year'] = pd.to_numeric(edu_students['Year'], errors='coerce').astype('Int64')
edu_students['Student Count'] = pd.to_numeric(edu_students['Student Count'], errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with missing critical values
edu_students.dropna(subset=['Year', 'Suburb', 'Student Count'], inplace=True)

# Fill any remaining missing student counts with 0
edu_students['Student Count'] = edu_students['Student Count'].fillna(0)

# Aggregate student data by suburb and year
students_agg = edu_students.groupby(['Year', 'Suburb'])['Student Count'].sum().reset_index()


# =============================
# 2. Clean and Prepare Business Data
# =============================
# Rename columns
business_df.rename(columns={
    "census_year": "Year",
    "clue_small_area": "Suburb",
    "anzsic_indusrty": "ANZSIC Industry",
    "clue_industry": "CLUE Industry",
    "business_size": "Business Size",
    "total_establishments": "Business Count",
    "total_jobs": "Jobs"
}, inplace=True)

# Aggregate by Year and Suburb
business_agg = business_df.groupby(['Year', 'Suburb']).agg({
    'Business Count': 'sum',
    'Jobs': 'sum'
}).reset_index()

# Standardise suburb names
business_agg['Suburb'] = business_agg['Suburb'].str.strip().str.replace(r'\s*\(.*?\)', '', regex=True).str.title()
students_agg['Suburb'] = students_agg['Suburb'].str.strip().str.replace(r'\s*\(.*?\)', '', regex=True).str.title()

# Convert numeric fields and handle nulls
business_agg['Year'] = pd.to_numeric(business_agg['Year'], errors='coerce').astype('Int64')
business_agg['Business Count'] = pd.to_numeric(business_agg['Business Count'], errors='coerce')
business_agg['Jobs'] = pd.to_numeric(business_agg['Jobs'], errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with missing critical values
business_agg.dropna(subset=['Year', 'Suburb', 'Business Count'], inplace=True)

# Fill missing jobs with 0
business_agg['Jobs'] = business_agg['Jobs'].fillna(0)

Data Merging and Correlation Analysis

This code block performs the following key tasks:

  1. Merge Datasets to combine the aggregated student and business data into a single dataframe (merged_df) on Year and Suburb.This allows for joint analysis of student attendance and business activity.

  2. Ensure numeric columns are correct by converting Student Count, Business Count, and Jobs to numeric types, handling any non-numeric or missing values.

  3. Correlation Analysis: Computes the correlation between Student Count, Business Count, and Jobs. This helps identify potential relationships or dependencies between student presence and business activity in different suburbs

Data Aggregation by Suburb

To prepare the dataset for analysis, we aggregated student and business data at the suburb level:

  • Students by Suburb:
    The total number of students in each suburb was calculated by grouping the students_df dataset by Suburb and summing the Student Count.
    This provides a clear view of the distribution of the student population across different suburbs.

  • Businesses by Suburb and Industry:
    The business_df dataset was grouped by both Suburb and ANZSIC Industry`.
    For each group, we calculated:

    • Business Count: Total number of businesses.
    • Jobs: Total number of jobs associated with those businesses.
In[13]:
# Aggregate students by suburb
students_suburb = students_df.groupby("Suburb", as_index=False)["Student Count"].sum()

# Aggregate businesses by suburb
business_suburb = business_df.groupby(["Suburb", "ANZSIC Industry"], as_index=False).agg({
    "Business Count": "sum",
    "Jobs": "sum"
})

Geocoding Suburbs

To enable spatial mapping, we used the Geopy Nominatim geocoder to retrieve latitude and longitude coordinates for each suburb in Melbourne.

  • A custom function get_lat_lon() was defined to query the geocoder and return coordinates.
  • A 'cache' dictionary was implemented to avoid redundant API calls for the same suburb.
  • Coordinates were added as new lat and lon columns to both the students_suburb and business_suburb datasets.

This step ensures that each suburb can be accurately plotted on interactive Folium maps and visualisations.

In[14]:
from geopy.geocoders import Nominatim
import pandas as pd
import time

geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="melbourne_mapper")
cache = {}

def get_lat_lon(suburb):
    if suburb in cache:
        return cache[suburb]
    try:
        location = geolocator.geocode(
            f"{suburb}, Melbourne, Australia",
            timeout=10   #  timeout
        )
        if location:
            cache[suburb] = (location.latitude, location.longitude)
            return location.latitude, location.longitude
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error with {suburb}: {e}")
        return None, None
    return None, None

# Add coordinates to students suburb dataset
students_suburb[['lat','lon']] = students_suburb['Suburb'].apply(
    lambda x: pd.Series(get_lat_lon(x))
)
time.sleep(1)

# Add coordinates to business suburb dataset
business_suburb[['lat','lon']] = business_suburb['Suburb'].apply(
    lambda x: pd.Series(get_lat_lon(x))
)
time.sleep(1)

Interactive Map of Students and Businesses

Using Folium, we created an interactive map centered on Melbourne to visualise the distribution of students and businesses across suburbs:

  • Student Population (Blue Circles):
    Suburbs are represented with circle markers sized proportionally to the student population.
    Larger circles indicate suburbs with more students.

  • Businesses (Green Markers):
    Each business cluster is shown with a green marker.
    Popups display suburb name, industry type, number of businesses, and associated jobs.

  • Marker Clustering:
    The MarkerCluster plugin was used to group nearby points, making the map cleaner and easier to explore.

This visualisation allows for spatial comparison between student population density and business activity, helping identify areas of alignment and gaps.

In[]:
import folium
from folium.plugins import MarkerCluster

m = folium.Map(location=[-37.8136, 144.9631], zoom_start=12)

# Students
student_cluster = MarkerCluster(name="Students").add_to(m)
for _, row in students_suburb.dropna(subset=['lat','lon']).iterrows():
    folium.CircleMarker(
        location=[row['lat'], row['lon']],
        radius=5 + row["Student Count"]/1000,  # size by population
        popup=f"Suburb: {row['Suburb']}<br>Students: {row['Student Count']}",
        color="blue",
        fill=True,
        fill_color="blue"
    ).add_to(student_cluster)

# Businesses
business_cluster = MarkerCluster(name="Businesses").add_to(m)
for _, row in business_suburb.dropna(subset=['lat','lon']).iterrows():
    folium.Marker(
        location=[row['lat'], row['lon']],
        popup=(f"Suburb: {row['Suburb']}<br>"
               f"Industry: {row['ANZSIC Industry']}<br>"
               f"Businesses: {row['Business Count']}<br>"
               f"Jobs: {row['Jobs']}"),
        icon=folium.Icon(color="green", icon="briefcase")
    ).add_to(business_cluster)

folium.LayerControl().add_to(m)
m

Observations:

  1. Melbourne (CBD) has the highest student count (~1.75M) and also a very high business count, making it the major hub for both students and businesses.

  2. Carlton, Southbank, and North Melbourne have high student populations but relatively fewer businesses compared to the CBD.

  3. Suburbs like Kensington, Docklands, Parkville, East & West Melbourne (Residential) have moderate-to-low student populations and much lower business counts, indicating smaller local economies or primarily residential areas.

  4. Overall, while student numbers vary widely, business counts are much more concentrated in the CBD, showing that business presence doesnt always scale proportionally with student population.

K-Means Clustering of Suburbs by Business Count & Jobs

This scatter plot shows the results of K-Means clustering on suburbs based on their business activity and job availability. Each point represents a suburb, colored according to its cluster, grouping suburbs with similar patterns of business counts and jobs.

The black "X" markers indicate the cluster centers, providing a reference for the typical values of each group.

This visualisation helps identify suburbs with high or low business activity and employment, enabling targeted insights or strategies for economic planning.

In[26]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Aggregate businesses and jobs per suburb
biz_agg = business_suburb.groupby("Suburb", as_index=False).agg({
    "Business Count": "sum",
    "Jobs": "sum"
})

# Merge with students for context (optional)
suburb_summary = pd.merge(students_suburb, biz_agg, on="Suburb", how="inner")

# Features for clustering
X = suburb_summary[["Business Count", "Jobs"]]

# Scale features (important for KMeans)
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)

# Apply KMeans (4 clusters as per your categories)
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42, n_init=10)
suburb_summary["cluster"] = kmeans.fit_predict(X_scaled)

# Cluster centers (for interpretation)
centers = scaler.inverse_transform(kmeans.cluster_centers_)

# Plot clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
sns.scatterplot(
    data=suburb_summary,
    x="Business Count",
    y="Jobs",
    hue="cluster",
    palette="Set2",
    s=100
)
plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c="black", s=200, marker="X", label="Centers")
plt.title("K-Means Clustering of Suburbs by Business Count & Jobs")
plt.xlabel("Business Count")
plt.ylabel("Jobs")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Cluster Insights:

  • Cluster 0 (Residential/Mixed-Use Suburbs) e.g., East Melbourne, Kensington. Suitable for policies focused on community infrastructure, local business incentives, and residential development. Suburbs show moderate-to-low student populations.
  • Cluster 1 (Major Economic Hubs) e.g., Melbourne CBD. Best for sustaining high-density commercial activity, workforce support, student services and large student population, confirming its role as the citys commercial and employment center.
  • Cluster 2 (Employment-Focused Suburbs) e.g., Docklands. Ideal for investment in transport connectivity, workforce mobility, and commuter infrastructure. These suburbs show high job availability relative to student numbers, highlighting strong employment hubs that may attract commuters
  • Cluster 3 (Student-Heavy Areas) e.g., Carlton. Optimal for targeted student amenities, housing, and recreational facilities. Suburbs have high student populations with moderate business and job presence, indicating areas dominated by student-centric activities

Key Observations:

  1. Student populations are concentrated in certain suburbs (Carlton, Southbank, North Melbourne), but business density is heavily skewed toward the CBD.

  2. The presence of businesses does not always scale with the student population, suggesting a potential gap between where students live and where economic opportunities are concentrated.

  3. Suburbs with lower business and job activity may require targeted development strategies to enhance local employment opportunities.

Recommendations for Policymakers

  1. Prioritise cluster-specific strategies: Align urban planning and investment initiatives to the characteristics of each cluster to maximise economic and social benefits.
  2. Support major hubs: Continue to invest in Cluster 1 suburbs to sustain their role as the citys primary economic and educational centers.
  3. Enhance residential and mixed-use areas: Provide incentives for local business growth and community infrastructure in Cluster 0 suburbs to strengthen local economies.
  4. Improve employment accessibility: Enhance connectivity and commuting options for Cluster 2 areas to leverage high job density.
  5. Cater to student populations: Focus on housing, services, and amenities in Cluster 3 suburbs to support large student populations.
  6. Regular updates: Refresh the clustering analysis with new demographic, business, and employment data to maintain relevance and inform policy decisions.
  7. Future scope: Integrate housing affordability, transport infrastructure, and economic development plans for a more comprehensive urban planning framework.

Conclusion

The analysis has provided meaningful insights into the spatial and economic characteristics of Melbourne suburbs. By grouping suburbs based on student population, business count, and job numbers, we can identify patterns that inform urban planning, resource allocation, and policy decisions.

By aligning policies with the characteristics of each cluster, city planners and decision-makers can promote equitable growth, optimise resource allocation, and enhance the livability and economic vitality of Melbournes suburbs.
